Starkweather, C. K., Gershman, S. J., & Uchida, N. (2018). The medial prefrontal cortex shapes dopamine reward prediction errors under state uncertainty. Neuron, 98, 1–14. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuron.2018.03.036

The authors trained mice on two nearly identical classical-conditioning tasks with odors that predicted a tiny water reward after a delay. In both tasks, the delay from odor to reward was the key thing that varied. Odor A had a variable delay drawn from 1.2 to 2.8 seconds; odor B always had a 1.2 second delay; odor C always had a 2.8 second delay; odor D had no reward. The only difference between the two tasks was reward certainty. In Task 1 the reward came every time for odors A–C. In Task 2 the reward came on 90 percent of those trials and was omitted on 10 percent, which made the true “state” of the world partly hidden on any given trial ("Might we be in the 10%?"). While the mice performed, the team recorded identified dopamine neurons in the ventral tegmental area and, in separate sessions, temporarily inactivated the medial prefrontal cortex by expressing a KORD chemogenetic receptor there and injecting its agonist, Salvinorin B. This let them compare dopamine signals with an intact mPFC versus a suppressed mPFC in the very same task structure. 

First they looked at the pattern of dopamine responses without prefrontal inactivation. In the fully certain task, reward responses got smaller the longer the reward was delayed, which matches the idea that expectation builds up with time, so the actual reward is less surprising when it arrives late. In the uncertain task, the pattern flipped. Reward responses grew larger the longer the reward was delayed, as if the animal’s belief was drifting toward “this is probably an omission trial,” which makes a late reward more surprising when it finally shows up.
-- So what they found was that later rewards (passing 2.5 seconds without a reward) are more compatible with "This is one of the 10% that's an omission," so your expectation swings around more when you do get rewarded. Sure. 

Critically, inactivating mPFC left the certain task’s pattern intact but erased the flipped pattern in the uncertain task. After mPFC inactivation, dopamine responses in the uncertain task no longer grew with time; many neurons now showed the same decreasing-with-time pattern seen in the certain task. Licking behavior and several timing-sensitive features of dopamine activity stayed intact, including sharp “dip” signals at expected reward times on omission trials and the small difference between 1.2 second and 2.8 second fixed delays, which argued that basic timing was not knocked out. 
