They then built a simple model to explain these results. The model that best fit the intact data assumed the brain keeps a running probability over hidden states: am I in the “reward will come” interval or did the trial actually roll into the unrewarded inter-trial period. Under uncertainty, that belief shifts toward “no reward” as time passes with no outcome, which makes a late reward produce a bigger prediction error. To mimic mPFC inactivation, the authors froze this belief update in the model. That single change flattened the time pattern of dopamine responses in the uncertain task while preserving timing-related effects, just like the real data. The take-home is specific. mPFC supplies the dopamine system with an evolving belief about hidden state, which shapes reward prediction errors when the world is ambiguous, while basic timing signals can come from elsewhere. 
